      <h1>Colors</h1>
      <h2 id="primary">Primary Color</h2>

      <div class="palette-container">
        <div class="primary">
          <div class="lightest"></div>
          <div class="lighter"></div>
          <div class="darker"></div>
          <div class="darkest"></div>
        </div>
          <p>The color of ripe, juicy persimmons which us wombats love to eat. The color of a warm, furry embrace inside of a darkened log under the dense eucalyptus canopy.</p>
          <p>We currenty use the instantly-recognizable npm red for many CTAs (calls to action), active tab highlghts and indication of link state. It also provides a background to header and footer elements of a most distinctive nature.</p>
          <p>We must be careful when we connatate the use of similar red with danger or error, as not to confuse skittish hoomans.</p>

          <h3>Example</h3>
          <code>
              background primary-lightest
              //. background #57381
          </code>
      </div>

      <h2 id="secondary">Secondary Color</h2>
      <div class="palette-container">
        <div class="secondary">
          <div class="lightest"></div>
          <div class="lighter"></div>
          <div class="darker"></div>
          <div class="darkest"></div>
        </div>
          <p>As the sun has set o'er the billabong long ago, the night sky illumniates with a glory of stars in the Southern Hemipshere sky.</p>
          <p>Our complimentary blue is deep enough to balance the contrast of the stark red. Midnight blue is currently in use merely as a background color, something to provide distinction and maturity to our product offerings.</p>
          <p>However, we must be careful ne'er to try to use this alongside the red for interaction elements, lest the color-challenged hoomans have to make distinctions betwixt the two.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 id="greighs">Greighs</h2>
      <div class="palette-container">
        <div class="greigh">
          <div class="lightest"></div>
          <div class="lighter"></div>
          <div class="darker"></div>
          <div class="darkest"></div>
        </div>
          <p>Only randos see in absolute, young padawan. Our use of greighs (neither gray nor grey) draw inspiration from the different shades of clouds roling across the Vancouver skyline - so very greigh, eh? Yet, as colorful wombats living in a mostly duotone world, we often use greigh ubiqutously as tint elements, content blocks and separators. We do define our black a bit lighter for legibility here at npm.</p>
          <p>Your legibility of greighs will vary across displays and devices, try to use them only as a background compliment to a layout structure.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 id="status">Status Tints</h2>
      <div class="palette-container">
        <div class="status">
          <div class="error"></div>
          <div class="alert"></div>
          <div class="info"></div>
          <div class="success"></div>
        </div>

          <p>What your status, you might ask? These complimentary colors will serve as our cues for all the elements of success and failure in our lives. OK - at least our lives as they relate to the submission of npm forms. The colors are purposefully muted somewhat, to allow for a bit of contrast between the overlayed icons and status descriptions. Don't use these anywhere else, as rainbow pastels doth not become thee.</p>
          <p>FYI - The error and the info and status message colors are tied to the red and blue primary / secondary variables.</p>

      </div>
    </div>

